00:15:02,700 --> 00:15:09,000
I started writing some, no, I'm not going to read you those names yet.

219
00:15:15,799 --> 00:15:20,133
And there's a certain point you just kind of instinctively know, ok, now I need to talk to somebody.

220
00:15:20,133 --> 00:15:25,966
Because you kind of feel like, ok, this is as far as I can go right now with what's in my head.

221
00:15:25,966 --> 00:15:28,399
Schafer: So I was thinking about this game.

222
00:15:28,399 --> 00:15:30,799
And I had an idea.

223
00:15:30,799 --> 00:15:32,966
Well, the first thing I did, well, forget about it now.

224
00:15:32,966 --> 00:15:35,000
Let me start over, ok.

225
00:15:35,000 --> 00:15:37,000
Gilbert: Would you like to read your notes?

226
00:15:37,000 --> 00:15:41,433
Schafer: And then you talk to somebody who you feel, ok, you're kind of taking a risk,

227
00:15:41,433 --> 00:15:46,866
because you're exposing all your ideas to somebody for the first time and they might laugh at you.

228
00:15:46,866 --> 00:15:55,933
Schafer: My idea for the story, the story idea for this game is about two stories, kind of happening side by side about a boy and a girl.

229
00:15:55,933 --> 00:15:59,533
And they're in totally different worlds and at different places.

230
00:15:59,533 --> 00:16:02,433
Gilbert: Different realities or just different places they go?

231
00:16:02,433 --> 00:16:05,033
Schafer: Well, that's a good question. That's an interesting question.

232
00:16:05,033 --> 00:16:07,933
Gilbert: I'm jumping ahead. Schafer: We don't know.

233
00:16:07,933 --> 00:16:12,799
Schafer: Mostly I just get this relief that I told somebody about the game and they didn't tell me it was stupid.

234
00:16:12,799 --> 00:16:16,333
But maybe they'll get inspired and they'll say a whole bunch of other things.

235
00:16:16,333 --> 00:16:21,299
Then you can take back into the cave with you and like, ah, now I have a whole bunch of stuff to chew on and like,

236
00:16:21,299 --> 00:16:24,133
ideas to bounce around and more dots to play with.

237
00:16:24,133 --> 00:16:26,399
It's hard to tell your ideas to people.

238
00:16:26,399 --> 00:16:31,533
Schafer: That mostly sets it up, except for my awesome story boards that I did.

239
00:16:31,533 --> 00:16:33,299
That was the idea for the intro.

240
00:16:33,299 --> 00:16:35,633
See, he's leaning, they're leaning against that wall and he's in a spaceship.

241
00:16:35,633 --> 00:16:37,700
And she's looking at a castle.

242
00:16:37,700 --> 00:16:39,899
Gilbert: And then you just choose then, one you want to start with?

243
00:16:39,899 --> 00:16:41,933
Schafer: Yeah.

244
00:16:41,933 --> 00:16:48,333
Schafer: The story so far, the reason I'm excited about it is that I've never done a story about this type, like this age of character.

245
00:16:48,333 --> 00:16:50,366
Like a coming of age story.

246
00:16:50,366 --> 00:16:59,366
About a boy and a girl, something about that the pairing of those like equal stories going on at the same time.

247
00:16:59,366 --> 00:17:10,766
And the things I guess that are interesting about that age to me are, it's an age where you're learning to take control and take some power in your life

248
00:17:10,766 --> 00:17:13,733
and also the responsibility that goes along with that.

249
00:17:13,733 --> 00:17:20,766
You know, you're learning that you have power in your life and you're learning you have the power to control your destiny.

250
00:17:20,766 --> 00:17:28,733
You have the power to hurt people and then kind of, you know, becoming an adult or becoming a young adult is about learning that

251
00:17:28,733 --> 00:17:31,833
you can grab the wheel of your life and steer it in a different direction.

252
00:17:31,833 --> 00:17:35,533
I think that's, but then you take the responsibility for what you've done.

253
00:17:35,533 --> 00:17:41,033
And now no one's telling you, you know, that you're going to be ok if you go in this direction, because you've chosen to do it.

254
00:17:41,033 --> 00:17:48,200
Gilbert: I think it's a really creative idea, but I don't think it's the kind of thing that we want to fund at this moment.

255
00:17:49,799 --> 00:17:53,066
Schafer: That's great. That's so funny because that's so crazy.

256
00:17:54,633 --> 00:17:56,799
Schafer: No. I mean, in some ways it's too early for feedback.

257
00:17:56,799 --> 00:18:04,466
I mean, unless I'm totally am like, stealing an idea from something, because you can't say whether an idea is good or not in some ways in the beginning,

258
00:18:04,466 --> 00:18:09,966
because so much is about the execution or the specifics of like how, you know.

259
00:18:09,966 --> 00:18:13,799
Because it's kind of, it's kind of a vague pitch in a way.

260
00:18:13,799 --> 00:18:22,433
It's like I want to do, I want to do this game that's about two stories, about a boy and a girl in really separate different worlds

261
00:18:22,433 --> 00:18:25,599
who are navigating this space in between them.

262
00:18:25,599 --> 00:18:28,566
You know, like that could mean a lot of different things.

263
00:18:28,566 --> 00:18:30,299
That could be told many different ways.

264
00:18:30,299 --> 00:18:32,633
So it's really hard for anyone to say like, oh, that's a good idea.

265
00:18:32,633 --> 00:18:40,333
But I mean, because I do have, you do have some idea of how you're going to do it but you can't articulate all of it.

266
00:18:47,366 --> 00:18:50,200
Schafer: I'm ready for you.

267
00:18:50,200 --> 00:18:52,166
It's like this, like this.

268
00:18:52,166 --> 00:18:55,166
No, don't use that one! Oh, god, it's going to be the one you use.

269
00:18:55,166 --> 00:18:58,666
I was doing my Magnum face.

270
00:18:58,666 --> 00:19:00,866
Dutton: I mean, I guess people have put money down.

271
00:19:00,866 --> 00:19:03,700
Some people have put a lot of money down.

272
00:19:03,700 --> 00:19:08,000
Are you feeling real pressure to make sure it's good? Like more so than your other games?

273
00:19:08,000 --> 00:19:12,833
Schafer: You know, people always ask that and I'm wondering what they thought I was going to do before.

274
00:19:12,833 --> 00:19:14,333
Dutton: Take it and run.

275
00:19:14,333 --> 00:19:16,533
Schafer: I can't wait to make this crappy game.

276
00:19:16,533 --> 00:19:18,000
Schafer: I don't know.

277
00:19:18,000 --> 00:19:23,266
I mean, I was scared about some things that will happen on the project, which is, did we already talk about people being disappointed?

278
00:19:23,266 --> 00:19:28,933
Well, once we talk about what the game actually is, we talk about this boy and this girl,

279
00:19:28,933 --> 00:19:35,066
there's going to be some people who are disappointed that it's not about an armadillo or spider or whatever they hoped it would be.

280
00:19:35,066 --> 00:19:37,000
There's a game.

281
00:19:37,000 --> 00:19:41,200
But it just collapsed from infinite possibility into this one particular game.

282
00:19:41,200 --> 00:19:44,933
The Internet: See, the Internet has just given you a lot of money.

283
00:19:44,933 --> 00:19:47,000
Over two million dollars.

284
00:19:47,000 --> 00:19:56,000
Now, if it appeared that you were wasting this money to make an inferior product, that would be very disappointing.

285
00:19:56,000 --> 00:20:01,033
Schafer: I think people who think, there're a lot of people who ask me, do you feel a lot of pressure now, are you scared?

286
00:20:01,033 --> 00:20:07,033
And I think they just don't realize what I do all day, 'cause a lot of my day is like, you know, in the past year,

287
00:20:07,033 --> 00:20:08,533
it's been like, look at the bank account.

288
00:20:08,533 --> 00:20:11,333
There's no money in there. I guess I'll fire everyone today.

289
00:20:11,333 --> 00:20:13,966
You know what I mean? That's, that's pressure. That's scary.

290
00:20:13,966 --> 00:20:16,766
Like I'm sweating now just thinking about that.

291
00:20:16,766 --> 00:20:18,900
And I don't have to worry about that for a long time.

292
00:20:18,900 --> 00:20:20,666
And that's great.

293
00:20:20,666 --> 00:20:28,966
But also, sitting around thinking about what my hero should do until Act Three, like that is the most easy, pleasant part of my day.

294
00:20:28,966 --> 00:20:35,766
You know, the time I spend locked in my office in the morning writing is like, I feel like I'm a kid again, 'cause this is like, that's the easy part of my job.

295
00:20:35,766 --> 00:20:41,166
And you know, over the past 20 years I've built a company, which puts a lot of things added onto that.

296
00:20:41,166 --> 00:20:43,700
Like thinking about business. Thinking about HR.

297
00:20:43,700 --> 00:20:49,900
Thinking about negotiating a deal with a publisher and thinking about payroll and then thinking about team management

298
00:20:49,900 --> 00:20:52,599
and who should be the next project leader and what game should they work on.

299
00:20:52,599 --> 00:20:55,133
And these two people aren't getting along.

300
00:20:55,133 --> 00:20:57,500
The building's going to turn off our power on Thursday.

301
00:20:57,500 --> 00:21:00,633
And there's all these things, like this is what, like the totality of the company.

302
00:21:00,633 --> 00:21:02,599
These are all things I think about.

303
00:21:02,599 --> 00:21:05,166
And just me sitting in my office with my notebook is like a little vacation.

304
00:21:05,166 --> 00:21:08,633
Like, you know what, then a spaceship could come down and yeah, it'd be great.

305
00:21:08,633 --> 00:21:14,666
So I'm having a blast with that stuff.

